<color=1.0, 1.0, 0.0>Civilization bonus:</color>
Rainforest Native Civilization - Cannot gather Gold. They do use Gold however, and they obtain it by purchasing chests of coin with Food and Wood at the Western Trade Post.
<color=1.0, 1.0, 0.0>Unique units:</color>
Carib Blowgunner, Lokono Clubman, Carib Prowler, Kalinago Axe Fighter, Carib Mantlet, Taino Pepper Bomber and Alligators.
<color=1.0, 1.0, 0.0>Unique buildings:</color>
Western Trade Post is a market that allows the Caribs to purchase chests of coin, Caribbean Tree Plot is an infinite source of wood that benefits from all woodcutting upgrades, and Native Gathering House trains units (mostly cavalry) from other tribes.
<color=1.0, 1.0, 0.0>Unique Ceremonies:</color>
Water Ceremony and Carib Race Ceremony

At the time of Spanish contact, the Caribs were one of the dominant groups in the Caribbean, which owes its name to them. They lived throughout northeastern South America, Trinidad and Tobago, Barbados, the Windward Islands, Dominica, and possibly the southern Leeward Islands.

Originally the Temenggong of Johor, Sultan Abu Bakar ibni Temenggong Ibrahim gains his power through political and military means. He is an Anglophile and thus western minded, focusing more on development than premature actions.

Sultan Abdurahman Pakunataningrat is the son of Panembahan Sumolo. He continues his father's policy of the modernization and reformation of the Sumenep state into a culturally significant sultanate. A devout sufi, he also transliterates many Javanese poetry works into latin.

A descendant of the royal family, Cut Nyak Dhien has long involved in the Acehnese military struggle. Her hatred towards the Dutch is not unreasonable, for the kaphe ulanda has killed both his first and second husband.

Sultan Abdulhamid Erucakra, or better known for his previous princely title Pangeran Diponegoro, is the eldest son of Hamengkubuwono III through a concubine mother. A devout shattarii and turcophile, he models his army according to the trending Ottoman style.
An eccentric ruler, the reign of Susuhunan Pakubuwana IX sees the westernization of the Surakartan imperial court. He combines the Javanese values with European, mainly Spanish, touches.

Nicknamed as Sultan Sugih due to his wealth, Sri Sultan Hamengkubuwana VII is an effective economic leader. Under his leadership the Yogyakartan Sultanate flourishes, especially due to the booming sugar industries.

Following the military tradition of his ancestry, Duke Mangkunegara IV has been trained in the art of war since his childhood. His legion is the strongest lijfwacht army in Java and he balances it with the flourishing sugar enterprise.

Sultan Ageng Tirtayasa gets his name due to his constructions of aqueducts and watering system. He rules over a vast sultanate which stretch from West Priangan highland to the Lampung hinterland. He enlists Bantenese, Sundanese, and Lampunger soldiers in his army.

Although he is just one leader of the Paderi among many, Imam Bonjol proves himself as the last to resist the Dutch occupation of Minangkabau highlands. He seeks the purity of Islamic teaching and will destroy anything that obstructs his path.

Born from a heiress presumtive mother and a grand vizier father, Sultan Abdul Rahman II inherits both the ceremonial and temporal titles. His reign sees the rise of the Malay nationalism and among the first political struggle against the Dutch hegemony.

Sultan Abdul Samad of Selangor is one of four rulers of the Malay states which are incorporated in to the Federated Malay States. His reign saw the unification of peninsular Malay states and the construction of magnificent buildings.
Aging up requires some coffee plantations to be built. Unit gathering rate is increased according to the number of Kumetir. Warga trickles coin while working. Best units: Panurung, Sentana.

Pangeran Suria Kusumah Adinata is not a king, but a count. He is nicknamed the Rich Count due to his wealth. He successfully maintains the Preangerstelsel for his profit and also arranges massive political marriages to unite the Priangan counties.

Sisingamangaraja XII is the last priest-king of the Toba people in Bakkara. He resists the incoming zending and Dutch colonialism, thus declaring war to defend his ancestry land.
